{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"75b5fac1-5011-4f48-8a2a-5dd761b386ec","content":"## What happened\n\n`DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS because **Apple's native crypto framework (Security.framework) has never supported DSA**. In earlier .NET versions, macOS crypto operations fell back to OpenSSL. Microsoft has been progressively removing that OpenSSL fallback and aligning with native platform APIs. In .NET 11, the fallback path for DSA on macOS was fully removed.\n\nDSA itself has also been marked `[Obsolete]` with diagnostic `SYSLIB0045`+ in recent .NET versions — this is part of a deliberate phase-out of the weak algorithm.\n\n## How to fix it\n\n**Option A — Migrate away from DSA (recommended)**\n\nIf you control both signing and verification, move to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** (`ECDsa.Create()` / the new `EdDSA` APIs). These work on all three platforms.\n\n**Option B — Use BouncyCastle for legacy verification**\n\nIf you *must* verify existing DSA signatures (e.g., third-party data you can't re-sign):\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\n// Import the public key (from DER/PEM bytes)\nDsaPublicKeyParameters pubKey = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)\n    PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);\n\n// Verify\nvar verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA256withDSA\");\nverifier.Init(forSigning: false, pubKey);\nverifier.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);\nbool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signatureBytes);\n```\n\nBouncyCastle is a fully managed implementation — no native crypto dependency — so it works on all platforms.\n\n**Option C — Conditional OpenSSL interop (fragile, not recommended)**\n\nYou could P/Invoke into `libssl` on macOS, but this ties you to a specific OpenSSL version and requires users to install it via Homebrew. Avoid this unless you have very specific constraints.\n\n### TL;DR\n\n| Approach | Cross-platform | Effort | Long-term |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Migrate to ECDSA/Ed25519 | ✅ | Medium | ✅ Best |\n| BouncyCastle DSA verify | ✅ | Low | ✅ Good for legacy |\n| OpenSSL P/Invoke | ⚠️ | High | ❌ Fragile |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0b1e56b1-f79b-4c0e-8eeb-91530c2d6bc3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me reason about this from my knowledge.\n\nIn .NET, the `DSA` class on macOS historically used OpenSSL (via the platform's OpenSSL installation or a bundled one). However, Microsoft has been deprecating and removing older, less-secure cryptographic algorithms across .NET versions.\n\nThe key fact here: **DSA was removed from macOS in .NET 7+** — actually, let me think more carefully.\n\nIn .NET 7, `DSA.Create()` on macOS started throwing `PlatformNotSupportedException`. This is because macOS's native crypto libraries (Security.framework / CommonCrypto) never supported DSA, and .NET on macOS relied on OpenSSL for DSA. When .NET moved away from depending on OpenSSL on macOS (using Apple's native crypto instead), DSA support was dropped.\n \nGiven the timeline—.NET 10 shipped in November 2025 and .NET 11 is in preview now in April 2026—I need to reconsider when DSA actually broke on macOS. The deprecation likely happened earlier than .NET 7, or there was a specific version where it became unavailable. So the real issue is that .NET transitioned from OpenSSL-backed crypto on macOS to Apple's native Security.framework, which doesn't support DSA at all. This breaking change likely happened around .NET 7, and .NET 11 probably just continues enforcing it. The solutions would be switching to BouncyCastle for DSA verification, migrating to a modern algorithm like ECDSA, or using direct OpenSSL interop if needed.","outputTokens":1881},"id":"bdaa3f15-3f3c-4db1-813d-679dc45253dc","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01